Data Management

Spring 2015

Three categorical variables relevant to teen pregnancy are H1RP1-H1RP6 from the AddHealth data set. The AddHealth data set is loaded from the PDS package. Using the dplyr package, a new data frame NDF containing only three variables after renaming H1RP1-H1RP6 to GettingPregnant, SexuallyTransmittedDiseases, and AIDs is created.

library(PDS)
library(dplyr)
NDF <- AddHealth %>%
  rename(GettingPregnant= H1RP1, SexuallyTransmittedDiseases = H1RP4, AIDs = H1RP3) %>%
  select(GettingPregnant, SexuallyTransmittedDiseases, AIDs)
head(NDF)
  GettingPregnant SexuallyTransmittedDiseases AIDs
1               5                           4    1
2               5                           4    2
3               3                           5    2
4               5                           1    1
5               2                           2    2
6               7                           7    7

Responses of 9 for question GettingPregnant are recoded to NA.

xtabs(~GettingPregnant, data = NDF)
GettingPregnant
   1    2    3    4    5    6    7    8    9 
2615 1112  356  253   91    8 2039   29    1 
NDF$GettingPregnant[NDF$GettingPregnant == 9] <- NA
xtabs(~GettingPregnant, data = NDF)
GettingPregnant
   1    2    3    4    5    6    7    8    9 
2615 1112  356  253   91    8 2039   29    0

ggplot(data = NDF, aes(x = GettingPregnant, fill = GettingPregnant)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(title ="Is getting pregnant, at this point in your life, one of the worst things that could happen to you?", x = "") +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Getting Pregnant\nWorst thing\nIn your Life?"))

Changing the \(y\)-axis to percent:

ggplot(data = NDF, aes(x = GettingPregnant, y = (..count..)/sum(..count..), fill = GettingPregnant)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(title = "Is getting pregnant, at this point in your life, one of the worst things that could happen to you?", x = "") +
  theme_bw() +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Getting Pregnant\nWorst thing\nIn your Life?")) +
  labs(y = "percent")

Another approach to graph the categorical variables is to use the base function barplot().

barplot(xtabs(~GettingPregnant, data = NDF), col = c("green", "red", "orange", "brown"))

barplot(prop.table(xtabs(~GettingPregnant, data = NDF)), col = c("green", "red", "orange", "brown"))

Question AIDs asks “What is the chance that you would get the AIDs virus?” A response of 9 should be recoded to NA.

NDF$AIDs[NDF$AIDs == 9] <- NA
NDF$AIDs <- factor(NDF$AIDs, labels = c("Almost no chance", "Some chance", "Half and half chance","a good chance", "Almost certain", "Refused", "Legitimate Skip","Don't Know"))[, drop = TRUE]
xtabs(~AIDs, data = NDF)
